< Rate>

<Review>Dr. Mofid ( Mona ) was one of the best dermatologists that I have yet to see ; she was an awesome conversationalist  and by the time that my appointment was completed, I was not only treated for my dermatology problems - I left her office with a much better knowledge of my issues with melanoma ( skin cancer ).
Skin cancer is one of the most common types of cancer and it is on the rise because of the effects of global warming ; it is partially caused by the large amount of uncontrolled tons of CO2
that is relased into our atmosphere every day by the very products of our own existence - including noxious factory gas   emissions and chloroflorohydrocarbons (aerosol
cans) ,etc.- which are destroying "our protective  ozone layer" that protect us from our Sun's harmful UVA and UVB rays.
The rates of skin cancer - melanoma - and other environmentally acquired illnesses are rapidly rising in regions worldwide; the UV index has surpassed 11 in many areas - even in the southwestern USA -  and it is now necessary to check yourself for signs of keratoses if you spend a lot of time outdoors; even in the mountains where the air is thinner and exposure is easier.
Melanoma is one of the deadliest forms of cancer: The signs to watch for are a change in the colour, size, or shape of a mole or a darker skin area that feels scaly or rough to the touch; an area that seems painful or may itch or bleed when rubbed.
It is more common in light skinned people however,people with skin of colour are susceptible too, as it can be found on the palms of the hands, under nails or under the feet; even in the mouth.
It was easily treatable with a small device that my dermatologist used to "freeze it off" - the temperature is below 300¬∞F and it hurts like a bee sting for about a few minutes; then it falls off within a couple of weeks.
I highly recommend that those of you who spend a great amount of you time outdoors, do a "self-examination" every month or so and wear a broad spectrum sunscreen that is water resistant, which has an SPF - Sun Protection Factor - of at least 30 or greater.
Make an appointment to see Dr. Mofid, if you think that you may have found any signs of what you may think is an unusual growth on your skin and don't forget that cloudy days have little effect on the Sun's power.</Review><Pictures>None</Pictures><response>None<//response><Gmap_id>0x80dc072bd2b438eb:0x633b9de30ef2f565< /Gmap_id></record>

<GmapID>0x809bd5f5aefb6493:0x836b5a7767c4400e< /GmapID>< Text>
A short, dusty, steep hike to a great view. Little kids (and mother-in-laws) can totally handle this, but it is steep, so keep that in mind. Gorgeous views of the lake. Rocks are sharp, so be careful. Go in the morning when it's cool. Back your car in if you can; pulling out onto the road can be tricky. Parking area can fill up quick, too, so get there early. Overall a decent family hike. Go in matching outfits and take your holiday card picture!< /Text>

< name>
Lil' Bape<//name>
<Date>1549058329956</Date><rating>2< /rating>< Review>
Interesting theme all throughout the restaurant that you don't realize the time going by as you're waiting for your food because you're pulled in by all of your surroundings and table top.

Hostesses are welcoming.

Large selection of food to choose from (Breakfast - Lunch - Dinner - Desert) that is made to look like it was printed on a newspaper format.

Food came out fast & was delicious.

Overall, I like the design, food, staff, tv's, beer ^_^. If it were up to only those categories, It would have been a 5 star rating.

So, why did I give a 2 -star rating?

The only reason I gave this place such a low rating, even though I found most of it to be satisfying, I looked up above our table after we got done eating and I noticed that they don't clean as often as they should.

The back of their TVs had a thick layer of dust and you can see some of the dust getting blown by the breeze coming in the patio doors and that breeze comes straight from the ocean so it comes with some good pressure. You follow the wooden structure of the building and dust dust dust dust dust dust dust. No doubt in my mind that everyone who eats here eats with dust sprinkling down on their plate the entire time. Water with dust, nice.

In my opinion, get your employees to start cleaning the damn place or management....do it yourself cause it's clear that nobody really cares about the cleanliness and it doesn't fall back on anybody else but management.

Get it together because that filth will only become more and more noticeable.</Review>

<Review>Quirky combo beach/sports/Americana/dive bar rolled into one. The bar forgos the usual bar stools for car captains chairs on big coil springs. Made for a comfortable, laid back (literally,) bar experience.

Great beer list of mostly local or near local beers, mostly favoring the IPA stole which suited me but the selection was good so don't let that dissuade you if you don't like IPAs. Burger was a solid bar burger and good side selections. Menu was pretty extensive so most should be able to find something to their liking.

Great place and I'll be back!<//Review></record></dataset><record>

< Review>
I love the views here. We came in pre fathers day sat but called 1st to see if there was a wait for brunch, per employee no just walk in ,no wait for patio. The entire section on patio was reserved except for 2 tables. We brought our dogs knowing there is no issue for the patio and were told by the server that they were understaffed and they would not seat us although there was 6 people in the main restaurant... I spoke to manager who said he would seat us an one of the reserved tables immediately. I was't trying to cause trouble just looking for affordable food with dogs and a baby to sit outside. Aside from that little snag, the rest of our experience was great. I've been going her since they opened. Ocean views and cocktails with a large menu what more could you ask for. WE love the chili, burgers, pizza and the hoagies. Huge selection of draft beer that is ice. The decor in the place is fun to look at. After 11 on sat not sure about sunday they have a great local musician that play the ukulele, it is a nice way to spend kick off your weekend. if you are a redondo beach local don't forget to ask for the 10% local discount! cheers<//Review>

< Review>
Service here is the worst.

Night started with the hostess telling us we're 4th in line. We were waiting nearly 20 minutes. Then suddenly my fiancee noticed the hostess beginning to pack up the hostess stand.  If my fiancee didn't notice and ask me what is going on i would have not even asked.  we would have been standing there, ignored.   She told us the place is turning to open seating and to go find ourselves a seat, I asked her why she didnt tell us, she told us its not her job, her shift ended.   Have some common courtesy, we were your customers before your shift ended.

Then we found ourself a seat.  The waitress seemed nice at first.  Then our beers took 15 minutes to come out,  our appetizers were literally served WITH our dinner.  As if we ordered pretzel sticks with our meal as a side or something?  Finally,  we were completely ignored. most of the night.  Waitress never brought us salad dressing. Then she also let us sit there for an hour longer, never cleaning our table once.  we even ordered another beer AFTER her asking us if we wanted boxes. Instead, never cleaned our table.  The manager even was sitting on the other side in a booth, folding silverware. Never said a word.   I dont think i'll be eating here again. Left my fiancee with a bad stomach ache too.  I bet their kitchen is taken car of just as bad.

Oh and the food quality. NOT WORTH IT.  simple. not special.  not much flavor.  waste. its bar food.</Review>

< Text>
A good alternative to other Taiwanese tea places. Jazen has unique flavors, and the add real bits of fruit like lychee on top of your other toppings. Our favourites are lychee green tea with aloe Vera and taro milk tea with honey Bob's (yum!). The popcorn chicken is also delicious. There is an attached pho place, a bonus if you are hungry.</Text>

I would give negative reviews to this place if I could. Their customer service is horrible‚Äì‚Äìthe manager especially (as of January 2019) is *extremely* incompetent.

So, here goes: The restaurant messed up on an order that I made through Uber Eats. Maybe an honest mistake‚Äì‚Äìit happens. I ordered the Mango Mojito drink with boba (an extra topping), but upon receiving the order from the Uber delivery guy, I found that the boba was missing. Unhappy with my order‚Äì‚Äìas any customer would be‚Äì‚ÄìI called the restaurant to ask what happened. The lady that answered the phone was considerate; she offered a discount or free drink I could redeem upon coming there in person. I wanted some sort of written guarantee for my purposes, maybe an email or something, so I inquired. She routed me to the manager, which completely flipped the script.

First, he claimed that the Mango Mojito did not come with extra toppings. He suggested this as an explanation for why I did not receive boba with the drink. This was peculiar since the form presented on the Uber Eats website *by the restaurant* presented a myriad of extra toppings, including boba. Further, I was charged for the boba, too, so minimally I should get a refund. Completely ignoring what I said, he blamed Uber for messing up the order to the restaurant. I could maybe understand that logic in some situations, but definitely not in this one. Here's why. The restaurant fulfilled my footnote requests for less ice and sugar in a second drink that I ordered, so surely they would have seen that I asked for boba in the first drink. I probed the manager again‚Äì‚ÄìI asked him, "if I came to the restaurant right now and asked for boba with the Mango Mojito, then you give it to me?" He said, "Yes, but it would cost extra."

YES! And this is exactly what I did through Uber Eats, so please explain to me how you *can't see* that I ordered boba for the first drink, but *can* see my footnotes for the second drink? On top of that, he started going off on how 60 cents isn't that much, Uber Eats sucks, Doordash is better, and the kicker‚Äì‚Äìhow the Uber Eats delivery driver is in charge of making sure my order is correct. Oh ok, let me get this straight. Now the Uber delivery driver‚Äì‚Äìsomeone who merely transports food/drinks from point A to point B‚Äì‚Äìis in charge of making sure everything that was supposed to be in my order was there? Yeah, it makes perfect sense for the delivery driver to start inspecting my drinks for boba, less ice, and less sugar. Because of the inconvenience, I asked for a discount or free drink, which was reasonable since that is something even his colleague had offered me before. He said he had no jurisdiction and I should take it up with Uber. What is Uber supposed to do? The restaurant messed up my order, not Uber. The manager even conceded that it was partly their fault, but he still refused to compensate me for the inconvenience.

I thanked him for his time because there was no point in arguing with someone so incredibly out-of-sync with business ethics. What happened to "the customer is always right"? Point being, don't go to this place. Cupertino has a ton of other better pho and boba places.<//text>

<user_name>John Bott< /user_name><text>Everyone loves a good story especially if there is a happy ending. Our story is probably no different from other stories that begin with a challenge that had to be overcome and the path to overcoming that challenge. The challenge for my husband was his eyes were turning inward resulting in double vision, squinting to see things and his need to work exceptionally hard to watch programs on TV, play golf and do everyday things we take for granted.  Due to these problems his ‚Äúquality of life‚Äù was greatly affected.  At age 72, a decrease in quality of life has an overall dramatic effect on all the things we do each day.

Our path led us to Dr. Shira Robbins, Ophthalmologist, with several specialties, including eye re-alignment disorders, to seek help for my husband‚Äôs double vision, squinting to see and the related fatigue.  After an extensive evaluation, she thoroughly explained my husband‚Äôs problems were related to his eye muscles not correctly aligning the position of each eye.   She provided treatment options, one of which was to have surgery, to correct the problem. He decided to have the surgery because of his feeling of confidence in Dr. Robbins and her team.

Our ‚Äúhappy ending‚Äù after the surgery my husband no longer has double vision, no need to squint to see things and the fatigue has been replaced with increased energy to enjoy life.

Thank you, Dr. Robbins for giving my husband a happier and better quality of life!

My husband and I encourage older adults to seek out help versus thinking nothing can be done to help your vision or blaming it on ‚Äúgetting older.‚Äù Your vision problems maybe similar or different from my husband‚Äôs vision problems. Let Dr. Robbins hear your story and hopefully you will learn more about your vision problems and find a path.

We wish everyone a Happy Ending to their story

Linda and John Bott< /text>< userid>

<review>The worst!!
My daughter needed glasses at 1 yo and we had Kaiser- had to change insurances and since there are only a handful of pediatric ophthalmologist Shiley  was one that we Research that had reputable doctors. Well first it took forever to get through the maze of numbers and receptionist, that were not helpful at all to even get an appointment and confirm insurance coverage.  Both doctors we researched that were pediatric were unavailable but we were told that the other doc could help and were pediatric as well. We went for the first appointment and they didn‚Äôt have us with the right doctor but again assured us that they could see our daughter. We were seen by 1 nurse 2 fellows another nurse and finally the doctor, who was in and out in 5 min, and suggested another appointment and another RX for her glasses. They also suggested that she might need surgery and that we should prepare for that just to be done.  We got the new prescription for my daughter and made another appointment 2 months later. At the 2 month appointment they double dilated her eyes, told us she needed a new rx  (and kids glasses are not cheap and most of the time need to be custom) and that we should look at surgery schedules since it is muscular and that can only be changed with surgery. We also needed to make another appointment in 2 months. We show up now for the 3rd appointment after 2 month and they tell us she needs surgery, a new RX and that we needed (like we knew we should have been and this was the first time it was mentioned)  to be patching her eye. We asked for a second opinion and they were annoyed that we asked. We reached out to her previous ophthalmologist for recommendations and a second opinion and she gave us the name and was surprised that Shiley saw us considering both of their pediatricians were out. Once we saw a new doctor for a second opinion he said that our daughter did not need surgery, did not need eyepatching, and that the prescription that she was given was completely wrong and was making her eyes worse. Luckily my daughter is doing much better now and is able to see with her corrected prescription. But then the nightmare wasn‚Äôt over, we were sent bills of over $1000 for the multiple appointments for out of network coverage since the doctors that did see her are not part of our plan, Even though the two pediatric ophthalmologists were. The whole thing left us upset, but it was the fact that the first thing suggested was surgery when my daughter did not need it. Go see anyone else

I came in for a 3rd opinion ophthalmologist visit on an eye issue I've been having. They rushed me into a bandage surgery, downplaying both how much it would affect me and how much it would cost. I thought I was just getting a contact in my eye - turns out I was bed ridden in pain for days, unable to look at any screens or brightness. I spent the first several days in excruciating pain which they said wouldn't happen, when I called to tell them about it they literally told me to "just stop using that eye". Oh thanks. We went from "you'll be able to work" to "just stop using that eye." When I saw the doctor a week later he was surprised by my reaction and downplayed it. Thanks buddy.

Anyway I just got charged 5k for a procedure I wasn't at all prepared for and would have never accepted. Lost over 1k in wages due to lost work. Staff needs to work on their communication. I've seen several ophthalmologists in the area and not all of them were good but they were all much better than this.

Oh hey they were taking great covid safety procedures though I'll give them 1 star for that!

***update*** any other san diego ophthalmologist would have charged me 300-500 dollars for what this place charged me 5k for.</review>

I am a stereotype that UCSD Medical Center could not see passed. In the last several months I have had to come to terms with the outright bigotry of the doctors I was subjected to and in their defense they were exposed to the anger I carried for a lifetime of being treated poorly for nothing deeper than the shade of my skin. I can‚Äôt say my despair began at UCSD, but I can say the reality of who I am did. I truly believed that my quality of life and their ability to help me would overcome any system mired in bigotry, I was wrong. You all may think this is a letter of injustice and frustration and maybe even a week ago it would have been, but now it isn‚Äôt. UCSD made me see my blackness, I proclaimed myself as a ‚ÄúTrue American‚Äù because I carried the blood of immigrant, native, and slave; but UCSD made me understand that what I am is Black and for that I am grateful to them. I know longer feel the need to straightened my hair or give credit to my Irish immigrant grandmother for the length there of. Now I walk in as a Black woman expecting nothing and no longer disappointed when that is exactly what I get. UCSD, you have shown me that I am self-created, and my dignity is not worth a cure I am truly grateful and glad in this lesson. I have never mentally felt stronger, despite my physical limitations. I looked in the mirror and saw me, it was my moment that you provided via doctors like your esteemed neurological ophthalmologist who spoke to his recorder (about me so was unable to speak to me). I listened as he made comments on my obvious health, though he did not know that I spent two days sitting to avoid exhaustion during his appointment or that I spent another day resting after. He rolled his eyes several times when I could not recall names and commented on my not wanting to have a disease that I seem to believe I had or in his mind, I wanted to have. I smiled when he turned his back on me with a final comment not even showing the common courtesy to hear my response. This time I did not walk out angry but exhilarated because I had decided what they saw was unimportant but what they allowed me to see was priceless. I think it will take several days to wash my blackness from him and I pray that he is able to do that, not because of forgiveness, I have none; not because of mercy, at this time, it is not in me. I wish it so that he will never know what is to be with someone who is strong and dignified even when people would cast you as otherwise. I will offer no names because in the end it is not the number of racist doctors I experience at UCSD but the very system that nourishes this bigotry that they are unequipped to handle, because despite numerous complaints from my people and action from the State they still do not believe it to be an issue. So I have decided to end my relationship with UCSD and accept that I will probably never run in hills with my son again, but even that is okay because I can sit and talk to him of my discovery of self  and UCSD's help in that. I must, however, acknowledge the Doctors , nurses, operators, and staff who despite this toxic environment treated me with nothing but dignity, consideration, and to the best of their abilities answers, and where no answers existed, they were humane enough to let me walk out with hope and those I will name. Dr. Deluba, Dr. Jewbleski, all the nurses that I have encountered, all the reception I have encountered, the phone attendants who had to process my anger when I could not and even the bigots because you taught something a textbook never could and in that I am glad.</Text>< pictures>

< review>
First cataract surgery went really well, great results.    Second cataract surgery I could see really well the  week after, though I had no more close-up vision    Then within a week later I had really bad vision and some Blurry  watery spots, and was told that it would settle down and I requested a visit anyway.   And sure enough  I had inflammation and fluid  in the eye which can happen with surgery but is very rare (macular Edema) and It took a couple of months of drops of two different types for it to subside somewhat.   When I returned I found out that I could have perfect distance vision with glasses which is what I had before surgery and I still didn't have my close-up vision and I still have blurry spots to go through my eye but I was told that I no longer have the fluid  and if I was really unhappy to come back in six months.    The doctor also told me that the insurance didn't cover it that getting a toric lens which cost me $1000 more would help my vision, and clearly it did not.  Then I got a letter that my new insurance is not covered by Shirley  and to find another provider so overall I'm very disappointed and yes on this last one I had to wait two and more than three hours for some of my appointments.  Having said this do I believe Dr Weinreb  is A great surgeon, absolutely.    Do I also believe and was told that complications can happen with any top surgeon in any top facility, absolutely.< /review>

< Text>
If I could give this postal branch 5 negative stars, that still would not be enough. So back in May 2020 I purchased an item on ebay and I received an alert when the package delivered I immediately went to my mailbox and the package was not there, because in the past I've received packages that belonged to a neighbor from the street behind me with my same street #"s I walked over there and my neighbor checked there were letters she had received in her mailbox but no package. I contacted my local postal branch customer service which is a total joke, they told me they would research it and when I talked to them I was told by Julieta that she could see it was delivered to an address across the street from my house (already acknowledging that they screwed up). I was told they would still have to reach out to the letter carrier. Well today 6/4/20 I spoke to another customer service rep Nancy, and I was told that since it was not insured and I could not file a claim even though they admitted to misdelivering it totally there fault, "there was nothing I could do". I have seen the horrible reviews for this postal branch and I can only think that  maybe they have some dishonest letter carriers that know when there is no insurance on a package that its a free for all. Again this is my personal opinion pretty sad we can't trust our postal service to do a decent job.</Text>

<Rating>5< /Rating><review>Not a whole lot that I can say that hasn't already been said. Various friends and I have used their dry cleaning service. This isn't 1 of those crazy fast same day types of cleaners, but I've always had good luck w/ them regarding time. I always get my clothes back the day of or earlier than when they say it should be ready.
Their quality of work has always been good. No mess ups. I and friends have brought all sorts of garments there (uniforms, suits, very large heavy body length coats to small light, fur, suede, leather, silk, polyester, cotton, etc.) always w/ excellent results.
Customer service has always been top notch and very helpful. Friendly, helpful, knowledgeable.
Pricing really runs the gamut, but it never seems overpriced. This isn't the $1 dry cleaner, but it's hardly expensive either, and anyway, the quality, punctuality, professionalism is worth paying slightly more than the super bargain basement bottom of the barrel places (I've had some bad experiences w/ the uber cheap places before). Simple things like uniforms, small items, regular shirts, pants, etc. are competitively priced. I've definitely paid much larger chunks of $ ($30+, $40+) for a single item there, but it's definitely warranted. That's for very large heavy items, heavily soiled items (like baby puke on my suit), and/or high end items requiring special care like fur, fancy sequins & embroidery, super high thread count wool, silk. They take credit cards as payment.
Hours seem pretty reasonable. They aren't open super late or crazy early, but it's understandable considering they're a small business.< /review>< pictures>

<Review>I have been coming here for quite some time, and I can say that they have been my tailor of choice in SF. I have tried many tailors throughout California, and divisadero height cleaners are the best. Service is excellent, owners are polite, and they always treat you fairly amongst all their customers. (hard to find in this town)

I have been reluctant to take my suits to just any tailor in fear that they might mess it up. However, based on some of the prior work I had done with them, they have done four shirts for me, which I am very pleased with. They understand the fit so the fitting is effortless.

Price is fair compared to the market for tailoring. However, when you factor in how good the garment comes out, you really feel like it is a bargain. I have bought quite a few suits from norstrom (sale) that I have taken there which now fit better than the one I have bought at Suit Supply.

<review>Short story:
Was busy day!

Had my hair done, my nails done, and my wedding dress put in for alterations at a place that valued my time.

What i wasn't done with are  customers with superiority complexes!

Long story:

I finally got my hair and nails done by myself after not doing them for over 10 years!

I have a wedding coming up in 3 days and brought my wedding dress to this place because of a recommendation from a friend.

As I was standing outside in the cold for God knows how long, this lady was inside arguing that she needed a zipper fixed on a wedding dress/jumpsuit. She shown the problem to both the seamstress and the assistant and expected them to get it done in less than 5 hours..... All tailor shops are closed and wouldn't even bother to respond let alone do a quick job for pennies on the dollar. She tried it on to show how severe the problem was and yet couldn't even fit in the leggings then told the staff that it wasn't even hers. The seamstress questioned the lady and the customer said she owns a rental bridal company and the bride can't wear it so was hoping the seamstress could fix the ladys mistake so the bride wouldn't know. All this is happening as my face underneath my mask dropped and the lady demanded it to be done by the end of the day. This is what I call a MODERN KAREN in their natural habitat. The seamstress then said politely that they do not do subcontracting work at all and has stopped for over 20 years doing that kind of work. The lady huffed and puffed out the door while snatching the jumpsuit back and the box it came in with out the door with crocodile tears.

Smile Direct Club has good marketing. The text based reminder system is impressively well polished. The iPad application they use to collect information was good except for two issues. One part had a date picker that didn‚Äôt let you change the month unless you change the year first which was non-intuitive. I‚Äôm a software engineer who makes user interfaces like these for a living and I couldn‚Äôt figure out how to make it work without assistance. The other issue was that in several places, you were expected to enter date information with the touch pad, which was very clunky. I‚Äôve never seen any software attempt to collect date information this way.

A blond woman who I assume was the general manager seemed slightly disgruntled, which seemed out of place with the customer focused image the company is trying to project, but I didn‚Äôt have to interact with her much.

The biggest issue I have to report about my experience was the demeanor of the technician who did my scan. I‚Äôm not the sort of person who requires or even likes a sappy contrived customer service persona, but I can safely say that her demeanor isn‚Äôt appropriate for a public facing role. She‚Äôd ask if I had questions, and then seemed impatient about answering them.  From the very beginning of the process, she made me feel like she didn‚Äôt like me and felt contempt towards me. Smile Direct Club has good marketing. The text based reminder system is impressively well polished. The iPad application they use to collect information was good except for two issues. One part had a date picker that didn‚Äôt let you change the month unless you change the year first which was non-intuitive. I‚Äôm a software engineer who makes user interfaces like these for a living and I couldn‚Äôt figure out how to make it work without assistance. The other issue was that in several places, you were expected to enter date information with the touch pad, which was very clunky. I‚Äôve never seen any software attempt to collect date information this way.

A blond woman who I assume was the general manager seemed slightly disgruntled, which seemed out of place with the customer focused image the company is trying to project, but I didn‚Äôt have to interact with her much.

The biggest issue I have to report about my experience was the demeanor of the technician who did my scan. I‚Äôm not the sort of person who requires or even likes a sappy contrived customer service persona, but I can safely say that her demeanor isn‚Äôt appropriate for a public facing role. She‚Äôd ask if I had questions, and then seemed impatient about answering them.  From the very beginning of the process, she made me feel like she didn‚Äôt like me and felt contempt towards me. I didn‚Äôt take it personally because I knew I hadn‚Äôt done anything to elicit this kind of response, but it still felt weird.</Text>

Traditional Dentist (TD) vs. Smile Direct Club (SDC)
TD: 40 min wait, over booking.    |      SDC: 4 min wait.

If they told me that, I would have simply cancelled then and there. But I was under the impression that I would get a FULL smile makeover because after all, my 3D photo images showed me the before and after of BOTH. NOT JUST THE TOP. Oh any by the way, I was gonna pay the same as someone else who got a top and bottom. I cancelled the account, sent back the aligners and received a refund of $250 from SDC. They said that they would cancel my account with HFD. I sent emails to HFD with attachments of my correspondence with SDC asking them to ensure my account with them was cancelled too. They emailed me back saying that my "account would be placed on hold until they could confirm my cancellation within a couple of weeks".  Needlesstosay that HFD drafted my account and I had to file a dispute with my bank. Now more than a month after my cancellation, I got a NOTICE OF PAYMENT DUE in the mail! Is this a joke?!? I have all the correspondence and evidence I need if HFD wants to take a legal route. I've never had such poor customer service in my life! I will never do business with HFD.  This is the most unprofessional, inefficient, and incompetent company I've ever had to deal with! EVER! SDC should do better for their customers! I would never recommend them either!< /Text>
